## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Also removed |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Obsolete, never thrown |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, leave locks held, and corrupt shared data. There is **no drop-in replacement**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative timeout.
    /// The work delegate receives a CancellationToken it should observe.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);          // throws if token fires
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call-site handling
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs After

```csharp
// ── .NET Framework (old) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 (new) ── callee must observe the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    // Pass token into cancellation-aware APIs
    return db.ExecuteScalar(command, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 async (preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await db.ExecuteScalarAsync(command, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **Cooperative cancellation is not automatic.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, the token does nothing if the work ignores it. You must pass `ct` into I/O calls or check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops.

2. **Uncancellable third-party code** — if you truly can't modify the work delegate, you can "abandon" the task but **cannot kill it**:
   ```csharp
   // Fire-and-forget fallback (the work keeps running in the background!)
   var task = Task.Run(() => LegacyBlockingCall());
   if (await Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout)) != task)
       throw new TimeoutException("...");
   return await task; // only reached if it finished in time
   ```
   This leaks the thread — use only as a last resort during incremental migration.

3. **`Task.Result` vs `await`** — `.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`. The sync overload above unwraps it; prefer the async overload to avoid this entirely.

4. **`WaitAsync()` is .NET 6+** — it's available in .NET 8 but doesn't exist in .NET Standard 2.0 if you're multi-targeting.
